    <item>
      <title>The Ticking Time Bombs</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/481/2025-02-25_the-ticking-time-bombs</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/481/2025-02-25_the-ticking-time-bombs</guid>
      <pubDate>Tue, 25 Feb 2025 15:10:29 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Hello, Govtrackers.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sorry about getting you a preview of this week in Congress later than usual. These are getting harder to write not because it’s harder to cover Congress, but because the work of the Legislative branch is being usurped by the White House. It’s depressing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House and Senate are in this week. The major policy question is what will emerge from the &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/RL33030.html"&gt;Budget Reconciliation process&lt;/a&gt;, an effort by Republicans to fast-track around Democrats and put their spending and taxation priorities into law. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Senate Republicans advanced a budget resolution out of the upper chamber on a 52-48 vote, but it doesn’t include everything that Trump has demanded. (They intend to move a second resolution with the rest of his priorities.) Now House Republicans will try to pass their own Budget resolution. This one will contain almost &lt;a href="https://bipartisanpolicy.org/explainer/whats-in-the-fy2025-house-budget-resolution/"&gt;all their priorities in one bill&lt;/a&gt;. The Senate held off on the more divisive stuff until later, but the House will try to swallow it in one big gulp. The big question is whether they can do so without splitting the party and killing the resolution. We will find out in votes they hold this week.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Another rapidly approaching crossroads is the Fiscal Year 2025 appropriations bills. FY 2025 started on October 1, but Republicans prevented the adoption of bills to appropriate (i.e. direct the spending of) funds. The government has been running on autopilot under a “continuing resolution,” which more or less kept funding levels at the FY 2024 level. But that continuing resolution ends on March 14th, and Congress must pass the appropriations bills to keep the government open. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;To pass appropriations bills, they will need Democratic support in the Senate and perhaps in the House. However, the Trump administration’s use of impoundment — when the White House illegally prevents the spending of funds already appropriated by Congress — is making it hard to &lt;a href="https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/time-is-running-out-lawmakers-scramble-for-a-deal-to-stop-a-shutdown/ar-AA1zxORG"&gt;strike an agreement over the spending levels&lt;/a&gt;. Democrats are insisting that the Trump administration follow the law and spend money as Congress has directed, but senior Republicans have indicated they want to give Trump a free hand, in other words, let him ignore the law. There is no incentive for Democrats to negotiate when any deal can be undone after it is enacted.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Making all of this more fraught is the need to address the debt ceiling. Republican demagoguery on raising or eliminating the debt ceiling means that some Republicans are unwilling to vote for such a measure, necessitating Democratic votes. The government already is using extraordinary measures to stay open, but at some point will run out of runway and will start missing payments to creditors. Should this happen, the financial markets will seize up and we likely will experience an economic catastrophe. When is the X date everything goes blooey? Best guess is &lt;a href="https://www.investopedia.com/the-u-s-has-hit-the-debt-ceiling-how-long-does-congress-have-to-fix-it-8778710"&gt;sometime in the spring or summer&lt;/a&gt;, depending on tax receipts.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On the &lt;a href="https://docs.house.gov/floor/Default.aspx?date=2025-02-24"&gt;House floor&lt;/a&gt; this week are a bunch of minor bills. There is, however, the very consequential budget resolution discussed above, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hconres14"&gt;H. Con. Res. 14&lt;/a&gt;, and a few resolutions to overturn regulations issued towards the end of 2024.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are 42 &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/02/24?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22House%22%7D"&gt;House committee meetings&lt;/a&gt; this week, including nine appropriations proceedings, five proceedings in the Judiciary and Oversight Committees, and so on. I’d keep an eye on the &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/house-event/117922?s=2&amp;amp;r=13"&gt;House Oversight Committee’s hearing with GAO Director Dodaro&lt;/a&gt;, today, Feb. 25, who will speak about the “2025 High Risk List,” which identifies which federal programs are most susceptible to waste, fraud, abuse, and mismanagement. This will be notable in part because it may address the systemic instability introduced by the new administration’s management decisions.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As usual, the Senate does a poor job of indicating what will occur on the floor this week. According to POLITICO, the Senate will continue to work through Trump’s nominations, starting with the Secretary of the Army and the U.S. Trade Representative. It may also vote on resolutions to undo late-Biden-era regulations.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are twenty-five &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/02/24?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22Senate%22%7D"&gt;Senate committee proceedings&lt;/a&gt; scheduled this week, with four proceedings before the Senate Armed Services committee and the Commerce committee. A good number of the proceedings concern nominations, including the nominees to serve as the deputy secretaries of Homeland Security and the Office of Management and Budget, the Deputy Secretary of Defense, the Directors of the Office of Science and Technology Policy and Federal Trade Commissioner, the Deputy Attorney General and an Assistant Attorney General, Secretary of Labor and deputy secretary, Secretary of the Navy, Director of the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, Deputy Secretary of Transportation, and more.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Confirmations and a GovTrack Expansion (We Hope)</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/480/2025-02-21_confirmations-and-a-govtrack-expansion-we-hope</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/480/2025-02-21_confirmations-and-a-govtrack-expansion-we-hope</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 21 Feb 2025 17:01:07 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Once again, Congress has had a slow week while all the action and energy seems to be in the Executive Branch even in areas clearly constitutionally reserved for Congress.  To that end, we're excited to announce that&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;WE'RE GONNA TRACK THE WHITE HOUSE&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/govtrack/alert-new-executive-order?ref=8f0vhi"&gt;Our New Kickstarter&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We're expanding our mission (if we can get enough subscribers) for a new newsletter tracking executive orders, DOGE, and other major official actions coming from the President and their appointees.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Just as we do for Congress, we’ll cut through the bravado and hyperbole: This is a project about what your government is actually doing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Plus, you can get a t-shirt.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Please back our project and share!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/govtrack/alert-new-executive-order?ref=8f0vhi"&gt;Our New Kickstarter&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Confirmations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://apnews.com/projects/trump-cabinet-confirmation-tracker/"&gt;AP's tracker&lt;/a&gt; with more information about the newly confirmed people.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;Lutnick, Secretary of Commerce passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s57"&gt;51-45&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Loeffler, Administrator of the Small Business Administration passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s59"&gt;52-46&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Patel, Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s61"&gt;51-49&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Hearings Ahoy</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/479/2025-02-19_hearings-ahoy</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/479/2025-02-19_hearings-ahoy</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 19 Feb 2025 14:36:09 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Good morning, Govtrackers.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate is in this week and the House is out.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We anticipate the major activity on the Senate floor this week are votes on whether to confirm Howard Lutnick as Commerce secretary, Kelly Loeffler as SBA administrator, and possibly Kash Patel as FBI director.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Senate committees have a mere &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/02/17"&gt;sixteen proceedings&lt;/a&gt; scheduled this week. Veterans Affairs will hold a hearing on Paul Lawrence’s nomination to serve as Deputy Secretary of Veterans Affairs, the HELP committee will examine the nomination of Lori Chavez-DeRemer to be Secretary of Labor, and Commerce will consider whether Steven Bradbury should serve as Deputy Secretary of Transportation. You may best remember Bradbury as the author of Justice Department memoranda providing legal authorization for torture.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There will be a HSGAC double-header on the nomination of Troy Edgar to serve as Deputy Secretary of Homeland Security and James Bishop as Deputy Director of OMB. The HELP committee will also vote on whether to advance Linda McMahon as Secretary of Education.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate Rules Committee will adopt its rules of procedure and vote on committee funding levels for the Senate. The Senate Judiciary Committee will hold a hearing on what it calls protecting children’s safety in the digital era, the Intel Committee will hold a closed hearing on an undisclosed topic, and the Senate Armed Services Committee will hold two hearings. We also expect to see a Judiciary Committee markup of a fentanyl bill.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Migrant Insider Repost: Who's Shaping Immigration Policy in the 119th Congress?</title>
      <author>Nicolae Viorel Butler       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/478/2025-02-17_migrant-insider-repost-whos-shaping-immigration-policy-in-the-119th-congress</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/478/2025-02-17_migrant-insider-repost-whos-shaping-immigration-policy-in-the-119th-congress</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 17 Feb 2025 15:47:46 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Good morning! The House is out this week; the Senate today Feb. 17 and Friday the 21st.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://migrantinsider.com/?utm_source=substack&amp;amp;utm_medium=web&amp;amp;utm_campaign=substack_profile"&gt;Migrant Insider&lt;/a&gt;, a newsletter headed by Pablo Manriquez and to which we subscribe and recommend highly, recently published a post of particular value to GovTrack users, especially those who are or plan to start actively advocating for legislation relating to immigration.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We asked if we could repost it here with credit and the fine folks at Migrant Insider said yes. The author is &lt;a href="https://substack.com/@nicolaebutler"&gt;Nicolae Viorel Butler&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://migrantinsider.com/p/whos-shaping-immigration-policy-in"&gt;the original piece&lt;/a&gt; can be found at their site.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;===============&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;WASHINGTON — While much of the media's spotlight on immigration policy has been on the Executive Branch, with President Donald Trump’s deluge of unilateral actions to shape immigration policy in the federal government, it's Congress that holds the purse strings—meaning: Trump’s schemes require Congressional approval and the colossal funding for his mass detainment and deportation operations.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;So it’s important to be aware and scrutinize the lawmakers that effectively control immigration policy where it really counts: the purse strings—especially in this Congress that has made immigration such a hot button issue.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The bad news for immigrants: since the anti-immigrant Republican party won a majority in the House and Senate, they hold the Chairmanships of the Committees and Subcommittees that pertain to immigration. Democrats are in the minority and thus they hold Ranking Member positions on these committees.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Chairmanships are extraordinarily influential because they typically control the workflow of committee business, including the public hearings and markups. As it is important to hold these people accountable, we’ve attached links to each person’s name so that you can be directed to their contact page should you wish to let them know how you feel about immigration in the United States.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Besides the Leaders of the House and Senate (i.e. &lt;strong&gt;House Speaker Johnson&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Minority House Leader Jeffries&lt;/strong&gt;, as well as &lt;strong&gt;Senate Leader Thune&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Senate Minority Leader Schumer&lt;/strong&gt;), these are the lawmakers who determine the role in immigration policy in the 119th Congress —&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;&lt;strong&gt;On the House Side&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;h5&gt;House Judiciary Committee&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jordan.house.gov/address_authentication?form=/contact"&gt;Jim Jordan&lt;/a&gt; (R-OH), &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Strong advocate for border security, supports enforcement-focused immigration policies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://raskin.house.gov/email-jamie"&gt;Jamie Raskin&lt;/a&gt; (MD-08), &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Favors comprehensive immigration reform, advocates for protections for Dreamers.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h5&gt;The Subcommittee on Immigration Integrity, Security, and Enforcement&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://mcclintock.house.gov/contact"&gt;Tom McClintock&lt;/a&gt; (R-CA), &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Promotes strict immigration laws, focuses on border security and deportation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jayapal.house.gov/contact/offices/"&gt;Pramila Jayapal&lt;/a&gt; (D-WA), &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Supports pathways to citizenship, opposes aggressive deportation policies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h5&gt;House Homeland Security Committee&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://markgreen.house.gov/contact"&gt;Mark Green&lt;/a&gt; (R-TN), &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Emphasizes national security, advocates for stringent border control.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://benniethompson.house.gov/contact/offices/washington-dc-office"&gt;Bennie G. Thompson&lt;/a&gt; (D-MS), &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Seeks balanced immigration reform, criticizes harsh enforcement measures.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h5&gt;Subcommittee on Border Security and Enforcement&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://guest.house.gov/contact/offices"&gt;Michael Guest&lt;/a&gt; (R-MS), &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Prioritizes border security, supports policies to prevent illegal entry.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://correa.house.gov/contact"&gt;Lou Correa&lt;/a&gt; (D-CA), &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Advocates for humane treatment of immigrants, supports DACA and family reunification.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h5&gt;Subcommittee on Oversight, Investigations, and Accountability&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://brecheen.house.gov/contact/"&gt;Josh Brecheen&lt;/a&gt; (R-OK), &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Focuses on immigration enforcement, criticizes perceived lax immigration policies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://thanedar.house.gov/contact"&gt;Shri Thanedar&lt;/a&gt; (D-MI), &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Supports immigration reform, emphasizes the importance of legal pathways and integration&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;&lt;strong&gt;On the Senate Side&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;h5&gt;Senate Judiciary Committee&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.grassley.senate.gov/contact"&gt;Chuck Grassley&lt;/a&gt; (R-IA), &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Strong advocate for border security, supports enforcement measures, criticizes sanctuary cities.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.durbin.senate.gov/contact/"&gt;Dick Durbin &lt;/a&gt;(D-IL), &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Proponent of comprehensive immigration reform, supports DREAM Act and DACA protections.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h5&gt;Subcommittee on Immigration, Citizenship, and Border Safety&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.cornyn.senate.gov/"&gt;John Cornyn (R-TX)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Focuses on border security, supports legal immigration but emphasizes enforcement against illegal immigration.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.padilla.senate.gov/"&gt;Alex Padilla (D-CA)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Advocates for immigrant rights, supports pathways to citizenship, criticizes restrictive policies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h5&gt;Subcommittee on Federal Courts, Oversight, Agency Action, and Federal Rights&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.kennedy.senate.gov/"&gt;John Kennedy (R-LA)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Concerned with illegal immigration, supports stronger border security.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.whitehouse.senate.gov/"&gt;Sheldon Whitehouse (D-RI)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Supports humane immigration reform, criticizes harsh enforcement.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h5&gt;Subcommittee on Criminal Justice and Counterterrorism&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.cotton.senate.gov/"&gt;Tom Cotton (R-AR)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Proponent of strict immigration policies, emphasizes border security, aims to reduce both legal and illegal immigration.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.booker.senate.gov/"&gt;Cory Booker (D-NJ)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Advocates for comprehensive reform, focuses on protecting immigrants' rights.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h5&gt;Senate Committee on Homeland Security&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.paul.senate.gov/connect/"&gt;Rand Paul&lt;/a&gt; (R-KY), &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Mixed stance; supports legal immigration but also stresses border security, sometimes advocates for less government intervention.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.peters.senate.gov/contact/email-gary"&gt;Gary C. Peters&lt;/a&gt; (D-MI), &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Supports immigration reform, focuses on solutions for DACA recipients, improving legal processes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h5&gt;Subcommittee on Border Management, Federal Workforce, and Regulatory Affairs&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.lankford.senate.gov/contact/"&gt;James Lankford&lt;/a&gt; (R-OK), &lt;em&gt;Chairman&lt;/em&gt;: Focuses on border security, criticizes lax immigration policies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.fetterman.senate.gov/contact/"&gt;John Fetterman&lt;/a&gt; (D-PA), &lt;em&gt;Ranking Member&lt;/em&gt;: Advocates for immigration reform, formerly supportive of Dreamers, pushes for humane border policies (though recently not so much).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;Anyway, if you follow us or read our newsletter, now you know why we so frequently go to these lawmakers for comment. To wit: It's because they play an outsized role in shaping our immigration policy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Thanks for reading Migrant Insider. Follow our work on &lt;a href="http://x.com/migrantinsider"&gt;X&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://bsky.app/profile/migrantinsider.com"&gt;Bsky&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.threads.net/@migrantinsider"&gt;Threads&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="http://reddit.com/r/congress"&gt;Reddit&lt;/a&gt;. To inquire about sponsorships, email &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/posts"&gt;sponsor@migrantinsider.com&lt;/a&gt;. Subscribe for $5/month or $49/year, if you haven’t already. Our work is made possible by the generous support of readers like you.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
